### OpenAPI / Scalar
GET http://localhost:5064/openapi/v1.json
Accept: application/json

###

GET http://localhost:5064/scalar/v1
Accept: text/html


### ── Chat (stateless) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

POST http://localhost:5064/api/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "prompt": "Give me a short watering checklist for tomato seedlings."
}


### ── Chat sessions ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

POST http://localhost:5064/api/chat/sessions
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "title": "Tomato planning",
  "capability": "seed-planning"
}

###

GET http://localhost:5064/api/chat/sessions?limit=20
Accept: application/json

###

# Replace with a real GUID from the create session response above
GET http://localhost:5064/api/chat/sessions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001
Accept: application/json

###

# Replace with a real GUID from the create session response above
POST http://localhost:5064/api/chat/sessions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001/messages
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "prompt": "Given my current setup, when should I start sowing cucumbers?"
}

### ── Garden Planner Chat (AI + auto-save) ───────────────────────────────────

# Ask a question – no action executed
POST http://localhost:5064/api/garden/planner/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "message": "What would be a good plant to put in pot 3 given the current moisture levels?"
}

###

# Planting intent – triggers SavePotConfigurationCommand automatically
POST http://localhost:5064/api/garden/planner/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "message": "I'm planting basil and tomatoes today – basil in pot 1 in the living room, tomatoes in pot 2 on the balcony."
}

###

# Multi-pot planting intent
POST http://localhost:5064/api/garden/planner/chat
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "message": "Set up pot 4 with cucumber Marketmore in the greenhouse, and pot 5 with lettuce Little Gem also in the greenhouse."
}


###


### ── MQTT / Sensors (Development) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
###
### To test the MQTT + mock sensor flow locally on your PC:
###
### 1. Start services:
###    docker compose up -d postgres mosquitto ollama
###
### 2. Start the HomeAssistant API (this terminal):
###    dotnet run --project HomeAssistant.Presentation --launch-profile http
###
### 3. In another terminal, subscribe to mock readings:
###    docker exec -it ha-mosquitto mosquitto_sub -h localhost -t 'homeassistant/test/mock-sensors/#' -v
###
### 4. Manual advisory summary topic:
###    docker exec -it ha-mosquitto mosquitto_sub -h localhost -t 'homeassistant/garden/advice/summary' -v
###
### 5. In yet another terminal, poll sensor readings from the API:
###    Repeatedly call: GET http://localhost:5064/api/sensors (once this endpoint is implemented)
###
### Each call to GetLatestReadingsAsync will:
### - Generate 6 mock sensor readings (in Development mode)
### - Publish them to MQTT topics: homeassistant/test/mock-sensors/<pot-id>
### - You'll see them appear in the mosquitto_sub output above
###
### To verify the Zigbee2MQTT provider on a Pi with real hardware:
### - Configure actual Zigbee2MQTT topics in appsettings.json under Mqtt:SensorTopicMappings
### - Switch to Production build (which uses Zigbee2MqttSensorProvider instead of MockSensorProvider)
### - The API will subscribe to those MQTT topics and cache incoming readings
###
